<div class="tab tab-pane active" role="tabpanel" id="mainTabPanel" aria-labelledby="showFullText">
<article class="article">
<p class="fulltext"></p><!--abstract content--><div class="hlFld-Abstract"><p class="fulltext"></p><div class="sectionInfo abstractSectionHeading"><h2 id="abstract" class="section-heading-2">ABSTRACT<div id="mathJaxToggle" class="hideElement"><label for="mathJaxToggle"><span>Formulae display:</span><input type="checkbox" id="mathJaxToggleCheck" name="mathJaxToggleCheck" /></label><span class="mathJaxLogo"><img src="/templates/jsp/_style2/_tandf/pb2/images/math-jax.gif" loading="lazy" alt="MathJax Logo" /><span class="qMrk">?</span><span class="auPopUp hideElement"><span class="pointyEdge"></span>Mathematical formulae have been encoded as MathML and are displayed in this HTML version using MathJax in order to improve their display. Uncheck the box to turn MathJax off. This feature requires Javascript. Click on a formula to zoom.</span></span></div><span class="math-settings hidden-lg"></span></h2></div><div class="abstractSection abstractInFull"><p class="summary-title"><b>ABSTRACT</b></p><p>This study is searching for some crucial physicochemical properties of groundwater samples collected from eleven outlets in Dakhla Oasis, Egypt, including the pH-value, electrical conductivity (EC), total dissolved solids (TDS), in addition to the concentrations of heavy metals and trace elements. In total 21 elements were analyzed using inductively coupled plasma spectrometry (ICP-OES). To categorize the water class: Chronic daily intakes (CDI), water quality index (WQI) and hazard risk (HR) were computed for the 21 elements in the water samples. Some biological parameters such as levels of urea, creatinine, and the tumor marker CEA were measured. The obtained results showed that the pH-values (6.12 to 6.56) for water samples are within the acceptable limits of the WHO. Results showed, also, that EC (274 to 532 Î¼S/cm), TDS (175 to 340 ppm) besides, the level of measured 21 elements were lower than the values allowed by World Health Organization (WHO) and US Environmental Protection Agency (USEPA). Additionally, the reached data were comparable to other internationally published figures. It is emphasized that the data obtained for WQI confirmed that water from all the sampling points was of expedient quality.</p><p>Based on the obtained data and the evaluated parameters, it can be concluded that the groundwater samples of the studied areas are of excellent quality; they do not pose any health risks to the local citizens, and are safe for their domestic consumption. Moreover, the results of urea, creatinine, and CEA analyses showed very few abnormal cases, which confirmed, again, that the groundwater in the studied areasdid not pose a risk to human health.</p></div></div><!--/abstract content--><div class="abstractKeywords"><div class="hlFld-KeywordText"><div><p id="kwd-title-d11641657e146" class="kwd-title">KEYWORDS: </p><ul aria-labelledby="kwd-title-d11641657e146"><li><a href="/keyword/Dakhla+Oasis" class="kwd-btn keyword-click">Dakhla Oasis</a></li><li><a href="/keyword/Groundwater" class="kwd-btn keyword-click">groundwater</a></li><li><a href="/keyword/Trace+Elements" class="kwd-btn keyword-click">trace elements</a></li><li><a href="/keyword/Heavy+Metals" class="kwd-btn keyword-click">heavy metals</a></li><li><a href="/keyword/Water+Quality" class="kwd-btn keyword-click">water quality</a></li><li><a href="/keyword/Health+Risk" class="kwd-btn keyword-click">health risk</a></li></ul></div></div></div><div class="pb-dropzone no-border-top" data-pb-dropzone="contentNavigationDropZoneAbs"><div class="widget gql-content-navigation none widget-none" id="d28d5637-3950-463d-a4f7-bc92bc490fff" >

<div class="wrapped " >
<div class="widget-body body body-none "><div class="ajaxWidget" data-ajax-widget="gql-content-navigation" data-ajax-widget-id="d28d5637-3950-463d-a4f7-bc92bc490fff" data-ajax-observe="true">
</div></div>
</div>
</div></div><!--fulltext content--><div class="hlFld-Fulltext"><div id="s0001" class="NLM_sec NLM_sec-type_intro NLM_sec_level_1"><h2 id="_i3" class="section-heading-2">Introduction</h2><p>Water is one of the main components of humankind`s ecology. It is considered the most crucial element for all living and inanimate systems on our planet. It is needed every day for all anthropogenic activities including the drinking water supply. Treatment of wastewater needs many analytical processes for examination (Aglan, Hamed, &amp; Saleh, <span class="ref-lnk lazy-ref"><a data-rid="cit0003" data-refLink="_i29 _i30 _i31 _i32" href="#"><span class="off-screen">Citation</span>2019</a></span>; Aglan, Mahmoud, Rashad, &amp; Saleh, <span class="ref-lnk lazy-ref"><a data-rid="cit0004" data-refLink="_i29 _i30 _i31 _i32" href="#"><span class="off-screen">Citation</span>2021</a></span>) and purification from heavy metals (Saleh, Aglan, &amp; Mahmoud, <span class="ref-lnk lazy-ref"><a data-rid="cit0027" data-refLink="_i29 _i30 _i31 _i32" href="#"><span class="off-screen">Citation</span>2019a</a></span>; Saleh, Mahmoud, Aglan, &amp; Bayoumi, <span class="ref-lnk lazy-ref"><a data-rid="cit0032" data-refLink="_i29 _i30 _i31 _i32" href="#"><span class="off-screen">Citation</span>2019b</a></span>) or other hazardous elements (Saleh &amp; Eskander, <span class="ref-lnk lazy-ref"><a data-rid="cit0029" data-refLink="_i29 _i30 _i31 _i32" href="#"><span class="off-screen">Citation</span>2020</a></span>; Saleh et al., <span class="ref-lnk lazy-ref"><a data-rid="cit0030" data-refLink="_i29 _i30 _i31 _i32" href="#"><span class="off-screen">Citation</span>2020a</a></span>, <span class="ref-lnk lazy-ref"><a data-rid="cit0034" data-refLink="_i29 _i30 _i31 _i32" href="#"><span class="off-screen">Citation</span>2020b</a></span>) to be suitable for reuse<b>, furthermore, the solid residues generated during the treatment process must be disposed of after stabilization using cost-effective materials such as cement (Saleh, <span class="ref-lnk lazy-ref"><a data-rid="cit0025" data-refLink="_i29 _i30 _i31 _i32" href="#"><span class="off-screen">Citation</span>2014</a></span>; Saleh et al., <span class="ref-lnk lazy-ref"><a data-rid="cit0033" data-refLink="_i29 _i30 _i31 _i32" href="#"><span class="off-screen">Citation</span>2020a</a></span>, <span class="ref-lnk lazy-ref"><a data-rid="cit0028" data-refLink="_i29 _i30 _i31 _i32" href="#"><span class="off-screen">Citation</span>2019b</a></span>; Saleh and Eskander, <span class="ref-lnk lazy-ref"><a data-rid="cit0026" data-refLink="_i29 _i30 _i31 _i32" href="#"><span class="off-screen">Citation</span>2019</a></span>).</b> Especially groundwater is an important source of water in Egypt. However, essential elements such as phosphorus have to be removed from surface water bodies for the growing of plants and the rearing of animals (Nkansah, Donkoh, Akoto, &amp; Ephraim, <span class="ref-lnk lazy-ref"><a data-rid="cit0020" data-refLink="_i29 _i30 _i31 _i32" href="#"><span class="off-screen">Citation</span>2019</a></span>). Therefore, assessment of groundwater quality for domestic and irrigation uses is one of the most important issues (Houria, Mahdi, &amp; Zohra, <span class="ref-lnk lazy-ref"><a data-rid="cit0011" data-refLink="_i29 _i30 _i31 _i32" href="#"><span class="off-screen">Citation</span>2020</a></span>; Hussain &amp; Abed, <span class="ref-lnk lazy-ref"><a data-rid="cit0012" data-refLink="_i29 _i30 _i31 _i32" href="#"><span class="off-screen">Citation</span>2019</a></span>)</p><p>Egypt is strongly committed to evaluate and guarantee water quality for use in agriculture and manufacturing activities. Therefore, physical, chemical, bacteriological, and biological characterizations of water are decisive requirements to be considered before its use, especially for domestic purposes.</p><p>The Western Desert of Egypt has various geomorphologic characteristics comprising highland, plainsdunes, and depressions. A large number of desert oases are distributed in this region, which depends essentially on Nubian aquifers. This area is high about 400 m above sea level.</p><p>Dakhlahas located about 750 km from the Egyptian capital Cairo; this oasis is one of the western desert oases. The study area covers five locations of the oasis, namely, Mut, Rashda, Bhdkhulu, Qalamoun, and Qasr as shown in the attached map, <a href="#f0001">Figure 1</a>. <div class="figure figureViewer" id="f0001"><div class="hidden figureViewerArticleInfo"><span class="figViewerTitle">Groundwater quality and health assessments based on heavy metals and trace elements content in Dakhla Oasis, New Valley Governorate, Egypt</span><div class="articleAuthors articleInfoSection"><div class="authorsHeading">All authors</div><div class="authors"><a class="entryAuthor" href="/action/doSearch?Contrib=Saleh%2C+Hosam+M"><span class="hlFld-ContribAuthor"><a href="/author/Saleh%2C+Hosam+M"><span class="NLM_given-names">Hosam M.</span> Saleh</a></span> <a href="https://orcid.org/0000-0002-5889-3548"><img src="/templates/jsp/images/orcid.png" /></a>, </a><a class="entryAuthor" href="/action/doSearch?Contrib=Eskander%2C+Samir+B"><span class="hlFld-ContribAuthor"><a href="/author/Eskander%2C+Samir+B"><span class="NLM_given-names">Samir B.</span> Eskander</a></span>, </a><a class="entryAuthor" href="/action/doSearch?Contrib=Mahmoud%2C+Hazem+H"><span class="hlFld-ContribAuthor"><a href="/author/Mahmoud%2C+Hazem+H"><span class="NLM_given-names">Hazem H.</span> Mahmoud</a></span> &amp; </a><a class="entryAuthor" href="/action/doSearch?Contrib=Abdou%2C+Mona+I"><span class="hlFld-ContribAuthor"><a href="/author/Abdou%2C+Mona+I"><span class="NLM_given-names">Mona I.</span> Abdou</a></span></a></div></div><div class="articleLowerInfo articleInfoSection"><div class="articleLowerInfoSection articleInfoDOI"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1080/23570008.2021.2018540">https://doi.org/10.1080/23570008.2021.2018540</a></div><div class="articleInfoPublicationDate articleLowerInfoSection border"><h6>Published online:</h6>07 January 2022</div></div></div><div class="figureThumbnailContainer"><div class="figureInfo"><td align="left" valign="top" width="100%"><div class="short-legend"><p class="captionText"><span class="captionLabel">Figure 1. </span> Map of the study area in Dakhla Oasis, including the sample location points.</p></div></td></div><a href="#" class="thumbnail" aria-label="thumbnail image"><img id="f0001image" src="/na101/home/literatum/publisher/tandf/journals/content/twas20/2022/twas20.v036.i01/23570008.2021.2018540/20221215/images/medium/twas_a_2018540_f0001_oc.jpg" loading="lazy" height="258" width="500" /></a><div class="figureDownloadOptions"><a href="#" class="downloadBtn btn btn-sm" role="button">Display full size</a></div></div></div><div class="hidden rs_skip" id="fig-description-f0001"><p class="captionText"><span class="captionLabel">Figure 1. </span> Map of the study area in Dakhla Oasis, including the sample location points.</p></div><div class="hidden rs_skip" id="figureFootNote-f0001"><div class="figureFootNote-f0001"></div></div></p><p>Dakhla Oasis, the site under investigation, is a part of the New Valley (Al Wady Al Gadded) Governorate (Saleh, Mahmoud, Abdou, &amp; Eskander, <span class="ref-lnk lazy-ref"><a data-rid="cit0031" data-refLink="_i29 _i30 _i31 _i32" href="#"><span class="off-screen">Citation</span>2021</a></span>). Most of the citizens in the oases are farmers and animal herders. The area is inhabited by about 250,000 people who cultivate mainly dates, cucumbers, beans, maize, and other crops. Ground and pond waters, in addition to very rare rainfalls, are the main sources of water supply for all agricultural activities. Groundwater is obtained from boreholes, hand-dug wells, and springs. Therefore, a suitable water quality, especially for drinking water, is required for sustaining and enhancing socio-economic growth and development in this part of the country. However, groundwater is not always safe for living consumption, where, many compounds and elements can run into during its filtration through the soil and rocks.</p><p>The potential toxic elements of groundwater depend on the origin of the water, their journey to water reservoirs, nature of the land forming the reservoirs, the time of their formations, time spent inside the reservoir, the microflora and microfauna, the temperature, and other parameters (Khatri &amp; Tyagi, <span class="ref-lnk lazy-ref"><a data-rid="cit0014" data-refLink="_i29 _i30 _i31 _i32" href="#"><span class="off-screen">Citation</span>2015</a></span>).</p><p>Although the term âheavy metalâ has never been exactly defined, it has been broadly utilized in chemistry and was given such a wide range of meanings by different authors that it is effectively a rather vague term (Duffus, <span class="ref-lnk lazy-ref"><a data-rid="cit0008" data-refLink="_i29 _i30 _i31 _i32" href="#"><span class="off-screen">Citation</span>2002</a></span>). In the field of drinking water, the term âheavy metalâ refers to metallic chemical elements that have a relatively high density and are toxic already at rather low concentrations (Tchounwou, Yedjou, Patlolla, &amp; Sutton, <span class="ref-lnk lazy-ref"><a data-rid="cit0037" data-refLink="_i29 _i30 _i31 _i32" href="#"><span class="off-screen">Citation</span>2012</a></span>).</p><p>In the context of adverse effects of heavy metals on human health, exposure to environmental pollutants plays a major role in kidney damage. Heavy metals such as cadmium (Cd), mercury (Hg), and lead (Pb) in drinking water are adversely affected in general functions. High levels of these metals are nephrotoxic, and exposure to even low concentrations can cause biochemical disorders (Pollack et al., <span class="ref-lnk lazy-ref"><a data-rid="cit0022" data-refLink="_i29 _i30 _i31 _i32" href="#"><span class="off-screen">Citation</span>2015</a></span>).</p><p>This work was designed to evaluate the quality of groundwater from hand-dug wells and boreholes at five sites of the Dakhla Oasis, consequently, to assess the impact of the groundwater quality on the hygiene of the citizens there.</p></div><div id="s0002" class="NLM_sec NLM_sec_level_1"><h2 id="_i5" class="section-heading-2">Materials and methods</h2><p><a href="#f0002">Figure 2</a> illustrates the flowchart of the methodologies. The contents of essential trace elements as well as precarious dissolved heavy metals were analyzed and compared to the WHO guidelines published by World Health Organization (WHO) and other organizations concerned in offering safe drinking water to the citizens. Moreover, the hazards to some important biological functions, e.g. renal diseases, in the population of a defined sampling point of the area concerned, namely the Mut point, were evaluated. Consequently, it was intended to affirm the suitability of water of the area under study for all human activities, particularly for domestic usage. <div class="figure figureViewer" id="f0002"><div class="hidden figureViewerArticleInfo"><span class="figViewerTitle">Groundwater quality and health assessments based on heavy metals and trace elements content in Dakhla Oasis, New Valley Governorate, Egypt</span><div class="articleAuthors articleInfoSection"><div class="authorsHeading">All authors</div><div class="authors"><a class="entryAuthor" href="/action/doSearch?Contrib=Saleh%2C+Hosam+M"><span class="hlFld-ContribAuthor"><a href="/author/Saleh%2C+Hosam+M"><span class="NLM_given-names">Hosam M.</span> Saleh</a></span> <a href="https://orcid.org/0000-0002-5889-3548"><img src="/templates/jsp/images/orcid.png" /></a>, </a><a class="entryAuthor" href="/action/doSearch?Contrib=Eskander%2C+Samir+B"><span class="hlFld-ContribAuthor"><a href="/author/Eskander%2C+Samir+B"><span class="NLM_given-names">Samir B.</span> Eskander</a></span>, </a><a class="entryAuthor" href="/action/doSearch?Contrib=Mahmoud%2C+Hazem+H"><span class="hlFld-ContribAuthor"><a href="/author/Mahmoud%2C+Hazem+H"><span class="NLM_given-names">Hazem H.</span> Mahmoud</a></span> &amp; </a><a class="entryAuthor" href="/action/doSearch?Contrib=Abdou%2C+Mona+I"><span class="hlFld-ContribAuthor"><a href="/author/Abdou%2C+Mona+I"><span class="NLM_given-names">Mona I.</span> Abdou</a></span></a></div></div><div class="articleLowerInfo articleInfoSection"><div class="articleLowerInfoSection articleInfoDOI"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1080/23570008.2021.2018540">https://doi.org/10.1080/23570008.2021.2018540</a></div><div class="articleInfoPublicationDate articleLowerInfoSection border"><h6>Published online:</h6>07 January 2022</div></div></div><div class="figureThumbnailContainer"><div class="figureInfo"><td align="left" valign="top" width="100%"><div class="short-legend"><p class="captionText"><span class="captionLabel">Figure 2. </span> Flowchart of the methodology.</p></div></td></div><a href="#" class="thumbnail" aria-label="thumbnail image"><img id="f0002image" src="/na101/home/literatum/publisher/tandf/journals/content/twas20/2022/twas20.v036.i01/23570008.2021.2018540/20221215/images/medium/twas_a_2018540_f0002_oc.jpg" loading="lazy" height="500" width="397" /></a><div class="figureDownloadOptions"><a href="#" class="downloadBtn btn btn-sm" role="button">Display full size</a></div></div></div><div class="hidden rs_skip" id="fig-description-f0002"><p class="captionText"><span class="captionLabel">Figure 2. </span> Flowchart of the methodology.</p></div><div class="hidden rs_skip" id="figureFootNote-f0002"><div class="figureFootNote-f0002"></div></div></p><p>Medical and environmental scientists from the Radioisotopes Department of the Egyptian Atomic Energy Authority (EAEA) visited Dakhla Oasis in late summer 2014. Eleven random sampling points in five locations in Dakhla Oasis, namely Mut, Rashda, Bhdkhulu, Qalamoun, and Qasr were selected for groundwater sampling. The pH-value of water from different outlets was measured using a portable consort pH meter (Model P 314). The collected water samples were acidified with nitric acid (Sigma Aldrich), and then stored at 4Â°C in polyethylene bottles produced especially for preserving water samples till their analysis. The collected groundwater samples were sent for complete assay to the Central Laboratory for Elemental and Isotopic Analysis, Egyptian atomic energy authority.</p><p>The samples were filtered using filter membrane Simsii PES (Diameter 47 mm and 0.1 Âµm pore size). Some physicochemical parameters including electrical conductivity (EC) and total dissolved solids (TDS) were evaluated using a conductivity meter (Orion model 162, USA), where both are in a direct proportionality relationship (Sharaky &amp; Abdoun, <span class="ref-lnk lazy-ref"><a data-rid="cit0036" data-refLink="_i29 _i30 _i31 _i32" href="#"><span class="off-screen">Citation</span>2020</a></span>). The anions Cl<sup>â</sup>, SO<sub>4</sub><sup>2-</sup> and NO<sub>3</sub><sup>â</sup> were determined by using a BTXAN-5 separating column in a GBC ion chromatography, with the chromatographic conditions reported in <button class="ref showTableEventRef" data-ID="t0001">Table 1</button>, while HCO<sub>3</sub> was determined by titration method.<div class="tableViewerArticleInfo hidden"><span class="figViewerTitle">Groundwater quality and health assessments based on heavy metals and trace elements content in Dakhla Oasis, New Valley Governorate, Egypt</span><div class="articleAuthors articleInfoSection"><div class="authorsHeading">All authors</div><div class="authors"><a class="entryAuthor" href="/action/doSearch?Contrib=Saleh%2C+Hosam+M"><span class="hlFld-ContribAuthor"><a href="/author/Saleh%2C+Hosam+M"><span class="NLM_given-names">Hosam M.</span> Saleh</a></span> <a href="https://orcid.org/0000-0002-5889-3548"><img src="/templates/jsp/images/orcid.png" /></a>, </a><a class="entryAuthor" href="/action/doSearch?Contrib=Eskander%2C+Samir+B"><span class="hlFld-ContribAuthor"><a href="/author/Eskander%2C+Samir+B"><span class="NLM_given-names">Samir B.</span> Eskander</a></span>, </a><a class="entryAuthor" href="/action/doSearch?Contrib=Mahmoud%2C+Hazem+H"><span class="hlFld-ContribAuthor"><a href="/author/Mahmoud%2C+Hazem+H"><span class="NLM_given-names">Hazem H.</span> Mahmoud</a></span> &amp; </a><a class="entryAuthor" href="/action/doSearch?Contrib=Abdou%2C+Mona+I"><span class="hlFld-ContribAuthor"><a href="/author/Abdou%2C+Mona+I"><span class="NLM_given-names">Mona I.</span> Abdou</a></span></a></div></div><div class="articleLowerInfo articleInfoSection"><div class="articleLowerInfoSection articleInfoDOI"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1080/23570008.2021.2018540">https://doi.org/10.1080/23570008.2021.2018540</a></div><div class="articleInfoPublicationDate articleLowerInfoSection border"><h6>Published online:</h6>07 January 2022</div></div></div><div class="tableView"><div class="tableCaption"><div class="short-legend"><h3><p class="captionText"><span class="captionLabel">Table 1. </span> Analytical conditions for the determination of anions (Cl, SO<sub>4</sub> and NO<sub>3</sub>)</p></h3></div></div><div class="tableDownloadOption" data-hasCSVLnk="true" id="t0001-table-wrapper"><a class="downloadButton btn btn-sm" role="button" href="/action/downloadTable?id=t0001&amp;doi=10.1080%2F23570008.2021.2018540&amp;downloadType=CSV">

According to Hall (Hall, <span class="ref-lnk lazy-ref"><a data-rid="cit0009" data-refLink="_i29 _i30 _i31 _i32" href="#"><span class="off-screen">Citation</span>1998</a></span>), values for the relative standard deviation percent<div class="tableViewerArticleInfo hidden"><span class="figViewerTitle">Groundwater quality and health assessments based on heavy metals and trace elements content in Dakhla Oasis, New Valley Governorate, Egypt</span><div class="articleAuthors articleInfoSection"><div class="authorsHeading">All authors</div><div class="authors"><a class="entryAuthor" href="/action/doSearch?Contrib=Saleh%2C+Hosam+M"><span class="hlFld-ContribAuthor"><a href="/author/Saleh%2C+Hosam+M"><span class="NLM_given-names">Hosam M.</span> Saleh</a></span> <a href="https://orcid.org/0000-0002-5889-3548"><img src="/templates/jsp/images/orcid.png" /></a>, </a><a class="entryAuthor" href="/action/doSearch?Contrib=Eskander%2C+Samir+B"><span class="hlFld-ContribAuthor"><a href="/author/Eskander%2C+Samir+B"><span class="NLM_given-names">Samir B.</span> Eskander</a></span>, </a><a class="entryAuthor" href="/action/doSearch?Contrib=Mahmoud%2C+Hazem+H"><span class="hlFld-ContribAuthor"><a href="/author/Mahmoud%2C+Hazem+H"><span class="NLM_given-names">Hazem H.</span> Mahmoud</a></span> &amp; Some biological parameters were measured including kidney function (urea and creatinine levels), and the level of the general tumor marker Carcinoembryonic antigen (CEA) was quantified. Urea and creatinine were measured using spectrophotometric techniques according to the method of Tietz (<span class="ref-lnk lazy-ref"><a data-rid="cit0038" data-refLink="_i29 _i30 _i31 _i32" href="#"><span class="off-screen">Citation</span>1990</a></span>). CEA was measured using a radioimmunoassay (RIA) procedure according to Westgard, Barry, Hunt, and Groth (<span class="ref-lnk lazy-ref"><a data-rid="cit0041" data-refLink="_i29 _i30 _i31 _i32" href="#"><span class="off-screen">Citation</span>1981</a></span>).</p></div><div id="s0003" class="NLM_sec NLM_sec_level_1"><h2 id="_i7" class="section-heading-2">Results and discussion</h2><div id="s0003-s2001" class="NLM_sec NLM_sec_level_2"><h3 class="section-heading-3" id="_i8">Evaluation of groundwater in comparison to standard values</h3><p>The groundwater quality in a certain area is largely depending on the type and extent of industry, planting, and other anthropogenic activities in a geographical area (Banejad &amp; Olyaie, <span class="ref-lnk lazy-ref"><a data-rid="cit0005" data-refLink="_i29 _i30 _i31 _i32" href="#"><span class="off-screen">Citation</span>2011</a></span>).</p><p><button class="ref showTableEventRef" data-ID="t0003">Table 3</button> represents the measured water quality parameters for the groundwater samples collected randomly from the 11 different sampling sites. It is obvious from this table that levels of most elements, viz. As, Cd, Cs, Pb, Ag, Cu, Cr, V, Ni, and Co were below the detection limit (BDL). On the other hand, Se was detected in samples Nos. 3 &amp; 5, while Al and Zn were found in samples Nos. 3 &amp; 4. It is worth mentioning that Sr, Na, K, Ca, Mg, Mn, and Ba were detected in all of the first five collected samples. On the other hand, Ba, Fe, Mg, Ca, K, Na, Sr were found in the six outlets samples, whereas Mn and Se were not detected in samples Nos. 6, 8, 9, &amp; 11. Moreover, Pb, As, and Cs were found only in samples Nos. 7 &amp; 8.<div class="tableViewerArticleInfo hidden"><span class="figViewerTitle">Groundwater quality and health assessments based on heavy metals and trace elements content in Dakhla Oasis, New Valley Governorate, Egypt</span><div class="articleAuthors articleInfoSection"><div class="authorsHeading">All authors</div><div class="authors"><a class="entryAuthor" href="/action/doSearch?Contrib=Saleh%2C+Hosam+M"><span class="hlFld-ContribAuthor"><a href="/author/Saleh%2C+Hosam+M"><span class="NLM_given-names">Hosam M.</span> Saleh</a></span> <a href="https://orcid.org/0000-0002-5889-3548"><img src="/templates/jsp/images/orcid.png" /></a>, </a><a class="entryAuthor" href="/action/doSearch?Contrib=Eskander%2C+Samir+B"><span class="hlFld-ContribAuthor"><a href="/author/Eskander%2C+Samir+B"><span class="NLM_given-names">Samir B.</span> Eskander</a></span>, </a><a class="entryAuthor" href="/action/doSearch?Contrib=Mahmoud%2C+Hazem+H"><span class="hlFld-ContribAuthor"><a href="/author/Mahmoud%2C+Hazem+H"><span class="NLM_given-names">Hazem H.</span> Mahmoud</a></span> &amp; </a><a class="entryAuthor" href="/action/doSearch?Contrib=Abdou%2C+Mona+I"><span class="hlFld-ContribAuthor"><a href="/author/Abdou%2C+Mona+I"><span class="NLM_given-names">Mona I.</span> Abdou</a></span></a></div></div><div class="articleLowerInfo articleInfoSection"><div class="articleLowerInfoSection articleInfoDOI"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1080/23570008.2021.2018540">https://doi.org/10.1080/23570008.2021.2018540</a></div><div class="articleInfoPublicationDate articleLowerInfoSection border"><h6>Published online:</h6>07 January 2022</div></div></div><div class="tableView"><div class="tableCaption"><div class="short-legend"><h3><p class="captionText"><span class="captionLabel">Table 3. </span> Elemental analysis of 11 ground water samples in mg/L</p></h3></div></div><div class="tableDownloadOption" data-hasCSVLnk="true" id="t0003-table-wrapper"><a class="downloadButton btn btn-sm" role="button" href="/action/downloadTable?id=t0003&amp;doi=10.1080%2F23570008.2021.2018540&amp;downloadType=CSV">
Download CSV</a><a data-id="t0003" class="downloadButton btn btn-sm displaySizeTable" href="#" role="button">Display Table</a></div></div></p><p>The eleven water samples were free from the most hazardous heavy metal pollutants, viz. Cd, Ag, Cr, Cu, V, Ni, and Co, and all the results were found to be within the permissible limit according to WHO. It can be stated that the levels of Ba and Sr that were found in collected samples from the eleven sites are below the levels that have been reported to cause adverse effects in the scientific literature (WHO, <span class="ref-lnk lazy-ref"><a data-rid="cit0047" data-refLink="_i29 _i30 _i31 _i32" href="#"><span class="off-screen">Citation</span>2016</a></span>).</p><p>It could be stated that concentrations [mg/L] for all the elements detected in the groundwater samples collected from the 11 sampling outlets were lower than the maximum limits permitted for drinking water quality as recommended by (WHO, <span class="ref-lnk lazy-ref"><a data-rid="cit0043" data-refLink="_i29 _i30 _i31 _i32" href="#"><span class="off-screen">Citation</span>2004</a></span>), (WHO, <span class="ref-lnk lazy-ref"><a data-rid="cit0046" data-refLink="_i29 _i30 _i31 _i32" href="#"><span class="off-screen">Citation</span>2011</a></span>) (CCME, <span class="ref-lnk lazy-ref"><a data-rid="cit0006" data-refLink="_i29 _i30 _i31 _i32" href="#"><span class="off-screen">Citation</span>2001</a></span>). Therefore, water in the area under consideration is safe even for drinking usages regarding the heavy metal concentrations found.</p><p><button class="ref showTableEventRef" data-ID="t0004">Table 4</button> presents the analyses data for EC, TDS, and the most interesting anions in water samples collected from the eleven sampling points. It is clear from <button class="ref showTableEventRef" data-ID="t0004">Table 4</button> that the parameters ranged as follows: TDS (175â340 mg/L), EC (261â507 Î¼S/cm),<div class="tableViewerArticleInfo hidden"><span class="figViewerTitle">Groundwater quality and health assessments based on heavy metals and trace elements content in Dakhla Oasis, New Valley Governorate, Egypt</span><div class="articleAuthors articleInfoSection"><div class="authorsHeading">All authors</div><div class="authors"><a class="entryAuthor" href="/action/doSearch?Contrib=Saleh%2C+Hosam+M"><span class="hlFld-ContribAuthor"><a href="/author/Saleh%2C+Hosam+M"><span class="NLM_given-names">Hosam M.</span> Saleh</a></span> <a href="https://orcid.org/0000-0002-5889-3548"><img src="/templates/jsp/images/orcid.png" /></a>, </a><a class="entryAuthor" href="/action/doSearch?Contrib=Eskander%2C+Samir+B"><span class="hlFld-ContribAuthor"><a href="/author/Eskander%2C+Samir+B"><span class="NLM_given-names">Samir B.</span> Eskander</a></span>, </a><a class="entryAuthor" href="/action/doSearch?Contrib=Mahmoud%2C+Hazem+H"><span class="hlFld-ContribAuthor"><a href="/author/Mahmoud%2C+Hazem+H"><span class="NLM_given-names">Hazem H.</span> Mahmoud</a></span> &amp; In groundwater under consideration, hydrogen carbonate is dominant, followed by sulfate, chloride, and nitrate anions which might refer to rock origin. The differences in the most interesting cations dominancy, viz. K<sup>+</sup>&gt; Na<sup>+</sup>&gt; Mg<sup>2+</sup>&gt; Ca<sup>2+</sup>&gt; Fe<sup>2+</sup>&gt;Mn<sup>2+</sup>, may be due to exchange processes or mixing with other resources.</p><p><button class="ref showTableEventRef" data-ID="t0005">Table 5</button> indicated the calculated Pearsonâs correlation coefficients (<i>R</i>) between the different parameters in the groundwater samples. The matrix indicated perfect correlation between EC &amp; TDS (<i>R</i> = 1), which confirmed that EC is a function of total dissolved solids in the groundwater (Masoud, El-Horiny, Atwia, Gemail, &amp; Koike, <span class="ref-lnk lazy-ref"><a data-rid="cit0016" data-refLink="_i29 _i30 _i31 _i32" href="#"><span class="off-screen">Citation</span>2018</a></span>).<div class="tableViewerArticleInfo hidden"><span class="figViewerTitle">Groundwater quality and health assessments based on heavy metals and trace elements content in Dakhla Oasis, New Valley Governorate, Egypt</span><div class="articleAuthors articleInfoSection"><div class="authorsHeading">All authors</div><div class="authors"><a class="entryAuthor" href="/action/doSearch?Contrib=Saleh%2C+Hosam+M"><span class="hlFld-ContribAuthor"><a href="/author/Saleh%2C+Hosam+M"><span class="NLM_given-names">Hosam M.</span> Saleh</a></span> <a href="https://orcid.org/0000-0002-5889-3548"><img src="/templates/jsp/images/orcid.png" /></a>, </a><a class="entryAuthor" href="/action/doSearch?Contrib=Eskander%2C+Samir+B"><span class="hlFld-ContribAuthor"><a href="/author/Eskander%2C+Samir+B"><span class="NLM_given-names">Samir B.</span> Eskander</a></span>, </a><a class="entryAuthor" href="/action/doSearch?Contrib=Mahmoud%2C+Hazem+H"><span class="hlFld-ContribAuthor"><a href="/author/Mahmoud%2C+Hazem+H"><span class="NLM_given-names">Hazem H.</span> Mahmoud</a></span> &amp; </a><a class="entryAuthor" href="/action/doSearch?Contrib=Abdou%2C+Mona+I"><span class="hlFld-ContribAuthor"><a href="/author/Abdou%2C+Mona+I"><span class="NLM_given-names">Mona I.</span> Abdou</a></span></a></div></div><div class="articleLowerInfo articleInfoSection"><div class="articleLowerInfoSection articleInfoDOI"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1080/23570008.2021.2018540">https://doi.org/10.1080/23570008.2021.2018540</a></div><div class="articleInfoPublicationDate articleLowerInfoSection border"><h6>Published online:</h6>07 January 2022</div></div></div><div class="tableView"><div class="tableCaption"><div class="short-legend"><h3><p class="captionText"><span class="captionLabel">Table 5. </span> Pearsonâs correlation coefficients (<i>R</i>) for some parameters of interest for the water samples collected from the area under study</p></h3></div></div><div class="tableDownloadOption" data-hasCSVLnk="true" id="t0005-table-wrapper"><a class="downloadButton btn btn-sm" role="button" href="/action/downloadTable?id=t0005&amp;doi=10.1080%2F23570008.2021.2018540&amp;downloadType=CSV">
Download CSV</a><a data-id="t0005" class="downloadButton btn btn-sm displaySizeTable" href="#" role="button">Display Table</a></div></div></p><p>The table shows strong positive correlations, i.e. greater than 0.7, among TDS and all the analyzed parameters except for SO<sub>4</sub><sup>2-</sup>&amp; HCO<sub>3</sub><sup>â</sup>, for which moderate correlation values were 0.64 and 0.55, respectively. It is well known that; the developed groundwater salinity can be attributed mainly to those strong positive correlations. It worthy to notify that high correlation coefficients exist between Cl<sup>â</sup>, NO<sub>3</sub><sup>â</sup>, SO<sub>4</sub><sup>2-</sup>, Ca<sup>2+</sup>, Mg<sup>2+</sup>, Na<sup>+</sup>, K<sup>+</sup>, Fe<sup>2+</sup>, and Mn<sup>2+</sup> (<button class="ref showTableEventRef" data-ID="t0005">Table 5</button>). This can confirm that the various water samples have similar geochemical characterizations (Masoud et al., <span class="ref-lnk lazy-ref"><a data-rid="cit0016" data-refLink="_i29 _i30 _i31 _i32" href="#"><span class="off-screen">Citation</span>2018</a></span>). Moreover, weak correlation coefficients are found between HCO<sub>3</sub><sup>â</sup> and Mg<sup>2+</sup>, K<sup>+</sup>, besides Mn<sup>2+</sup> cations. This suggested that the hydrogen carbonate of these cations originated from oxidative carbon dioxide dissolution of carbonate-bearing rocks in the aquifer. A similar explanation for hydrogen carbonate occurrence in water samples was provided by Massmann, Tichomirowa, Merz, and Pekdeger (<span class="ref-lnk lazy-ref"><a data-rid="cit0017" data-refLink="_i29 _i30 _i31 _i32" href="#"><span class="off-screen">Citation</span>2003</a></span>). On the other hand, the small correlation coefficients between HCO<sub>3</sub><sup>â</sup>and SO4<sup>2-</sup> anions could be due to the very low ion exchange process between them in the aquifer environment.</p></div><div id="s0003-s2002" class="NLM_sec NLM_sec_level_2"><h3 class="section-heading-3" id="_i9">Groundwater interactions</h3><p>The levels of the soluble ions in groundwater are a factor of the hydro-geochemical processes acting on the water during its route to the final basin as well as processes taking place in the aquifer (Nayak &amp; Sahood, <span class="ref-lnk lazy-ref"><a data-rid="cit0018" data-refLink="_i29 _i30 _i31 _i32" href="#"><span class="off-screen">Citation</span>2011</a></span>). The levels of the different major elements in groundwater are used in the determination of geochemical processes. Various physical, chemical, and mechanical processes occur during rock-water interaction, which include erosion, freeze-thaw, dissolution/precipitation, ion exchange processes, oxidation, and reduction. The number of relationships covering Na relation with each of K, Ca, and Mg are discussed in the illustrations below.</p><p><a href="#f0003">Figure 3(a</a>) represents the scatter diagram for Na<sup>+</sup> versus Ca<sup>2+</sup> [meq/L] in groundwater from the 11 sampling places. Most points are located below the equiline of 1:1, which indicates a reduction in Ca<sup>2+</sup> concentration compared with Na<sup>+</sup> contents in groundwater, even when the area under study geologically is mainly limestone formation. This can be due to cation exchange during which Ca<sup>2+</sup> is replaced by Na<sup>+.</sup> (Ogunribido and KehindeâPhilips, <span class="ref-lnk lazy-ref"><a data-rid="cit0021" data-refLink="_i29 _i30 _i31 _i32" href="#"><span class="off-screen">Citation</span>2012</a></span>). <div class="figure figureViewer" id="f0003"><div class="hidden figureViewerArticleInfo"><span for the relationship between potassium versus calcium [meq/L] in groundwater from the 11 sampling places that it follows the same trend as seen for the relation between Na<sup>+</sup> and Ca<sup>2+</sup>, <a href="#f0003">Figure 3(b</a>). This can also be related to cation exchange, during which Ca<sup>2+</sup> is replaced by K<sup>+</sup>.</p><p>The scatter diagrams for the relationships between sodium versus magnesium [meq/l] shown in <a href="#f0004">Figure 4(a</a>) and potassium versus magnesium [meq/l], <a href="#f0004">Figure 4(b</a>), in groundwater from the 11 sampling places, exhibited a similar trend. Most points are located above the equiline of 1:1, which indicates a higher Mg<sup>2+</sup> concentrations compared with both the two alkali metal ions Na<sup>+</sup> and K<sup>+</sup> in groundwater. This can be attributed to anthropogenic mining activities not only in Bahariya oasis, where the Mg content in iron stone in this area ranges from 0.7% to 7.66% (Abouzeid &amp; Khalid, <span class="ref-lnk lazy-ref"><a data-rid="cit0001" data-refLink="_i29 _i30 _i31 _i32" href="#"><span class="off-screen">Citation</span>2011</a></span>), but also to many other developed mining projects in the Western desert. <div class="figure figureViewer" id="f0004"><div class="hidden figureViewerArticleInfo"><span class="figViewerTitle">Groundwater quality and health assessments based on heavy metals and trace elements content in Dakhla Oasis, New Valley Governorate, Egypt</span><div class="articleAuthors articleInfoSection"><div class="authorsHeading">All authors</div><div class="authors"><a class="entryAuthor" href="/action/doSearch?Contrib=Saleh%2C+Hosam+M"><span class="hlFld-ContribAuthor"><a href="/author/Saleh%2C+Hosam+M"><span class="NLM_given-names">Hosam M.</span> Saleh</a></span> <a href="https://orcid.org/0000-0002-5889-3548"><img src="/templates/jsp/images/orcid.png" /></a>, </a><a class="entryAuthor" href="/action/doSearch?Contrib=Eskander%2C+Samir+B"><span class="hlFld-ContribAuthor"><a href="/author/Eskander%2C+Samir+B"><span class="NLM_given-names">Samir B.</span> Eskander</a></span>, </a><a class="entryAuthor" href="/action/doSearch?Contrib=Mahmoud%2C+Hazem+H"><span class="hlFld-ContribAuthor"><a href="/author/Mahmoud%2C+Hazem+H"><span class="NLM_given-names">Hazem H.</span> Mahmoud</a></span> &amp; </a><a class="entryAuthor" href="/action/doSearch?Contrib=Abdou%2C+Mona+I"><span class="hlFld-ContribAuthor"><a href="/author/Abdou%2C+Mona+I"><span class="NLM_given-names">Mona I.</span> Abdou</a></span></a></div></div><div class="articleLowerInfo articleInfoSection"><div class="articleLowerInfoSection articleInfoDOI"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1080/23570008.2021.2018540">https://doi.org/10.1080/23570008.2021.2018540</a></div><div class="articleInfoPublicationDate articleLowerInfoSection border"><h6>Published online:</h6>07 January 2022</div></div></div><div class="figureThumbnailContainer"><div class="figureInfo"><td align="left" valign="top" width="100%"><div class="short-legend"><p class="captionText"><span class="captionLabel">Figure 4. </span> The relationship between the average dissolved magnesium and sodium contents or potassium contents [meq/L] in ground water from the 11 sampling positions.</p></div></td></div><a href="#" class="thumbnail" aria-label="thumbnail image"><img id="f0004image" src="/na101/home/literatum/publisher/tandf/journals/content/twas20/2022/twas20.v036.i01/23570008.2021.2018540/20221215/images/medium/twas_a_2018540_f0004_oc.jpg" loading="lazy" height="189" width="500" /></a><div class="figureDownloadOptions"><a href="#" class="downloadBtn btn btn-sm" role="button">Display full size</a></div></div></div><div class="hidden rs_skip" id="fig-description-f0004"><p class="captionText"><span class="captionLabel">Figure 4. </span> The relationship between the average dissolved magnesium and sodium contents or potassium contents [meq/L] in ground water from the 11 sampling positions.</p></div><div class="hidden rs_skip" id="figureFootNote-f0004"><div class="figureFootNote-f0004"></div></div></p><p>As the dissolution of Na+ and K+[meq/L] is prominent, in general, both contents were not far from the equiline (1:1) as shown in <a href="#f0005">Figure 5</a>. According to World Health Organization (WHO, <span class="ref-lnk lazy-ref"><a data-rid="cit0045" data-refLink="_i29 _i30 _i31 _i32" href="#"><span class="off-screen">Citation</span>2009</a></span>), humanâs sodium and potassium intake balance is very crucial; an excess sodium intake can result in depletion of potassium levels. Also, magnesium deficiency can result in failure to retain potassium in sufficient quantities, while an excess intake of potassium can interfere with magnesium uptake. <div class="figure figureViewer" id="f0005"><div class="hidden figureViewerArticleInfo"><span class="figViewerTitle">Groundwater quality and health assessments based on heavy metals and trace elements content in Dakhla Oasis, New Valley Governorate, Egypt</span><div class="articleAuthors articleInfoSection"><div class="authorsHeading">All authors</div><div class="authors"><a class="entryAuthor" href="/action/doSearch?Contrib=Saleh%2C+Hosam+M"><span class="hlFld-ContribAuthor"><a href="/author/Saleh%2C+Hosam+M"><span class="NLM_given-names">Hosam M.</span> Saleh</a></span> <a href="https://orcid.org/0000-0002-5889-3548"><img src="/templates/jsp/images/orcid.png" /></a>, </a><a class="entryAuthor" href="/action/doSearch?Contrib=Eskander%2C+Samir+B"><span class="hlFld-ContribAuthor"><a href="/author/Eskander%2C+Samir+B"><span class="NLM_given-names">Samir B.</span> Eskander</a></span>, </a><a class="entryAuthor" href="/action/doSearch?Contrib=Mahmoud%2C+Hazem+H"><span class="hlFld-ContribAuthor"><a href="/author/Mahmoud%2C+Hazem+H"><span class="NLM_given-names">Hazem H.</span> Mahmoud</a></span> &amp; </a><a class="entryAuthor" href="/action/doSearch?Contrib=Abdou%2C+Mona+I"><span class="hlFld-ContribAuthor"><a href="/author/Abdou%2C+Mona+I"><span class="NLM_given-names">Mona I.</span> Abdou</a></span></a></div></div><div class="articleLowerInfo articleInfoSection"><div class="articleLowerInfoSection articleInfoDOI"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1080/23570008.2021.2018540">https://doi.org/10.1080/23570008.2021.2018540</a></div><div class="articleInfoPublicationDate articleLowerInfoSection border"><h6>Published online:</h6>07 January 2022</div></div></div><div class="figureThumbnailContainer"><div class="figureInfo"><td align="left" valign="top" width="100%"><div class="short-legend"><p class="captionText"><span class="captionLabel">Figure 5. </span> The relationship between the average dissolved sodium and potassium contents [meq/L] in ground water from the 11 sampling positions.</p></div></td></div><a href="#" class="thumbnail" aria-label="thumbnail image"><img id="f0005image" src="/na101/home/literatum/publisher/tandf/journals/content/twas20/2022/twas20.v036.i01/23570008.2021.2018540/20221215/images/medium/twas_a_2018540_f0005_oc.jpg" loading="lazy" height="283" width="500" /></a><div class="figureDownloadOptions"><a href="#" class="downloadBtn btn btn-sm" role="button">Display full size</a></div></div></div><div class="hidden rs_skip" id="fig-description-f0005"><p class="captionText"><span class="captionLabel">Figure 5. </span> The relationship between the average dissolved sodium and potassium contents [meq/L] in ground water from the 11 sampling positions.</p></div><div class="hidden rs_skip" id="figureFootNote-f0005"><div class="figureFootNote-f0005"></div></div></p><p>Moreover, it is clear from <a href="#f0005">Figure 5</a> that there is a more or less balanced distribution for both sodium and potassium along their equiline of 1:1 in the tested waters. This indicates that there is a limited or equal ionic exchange between the two alkali elements, which consequently confirms the suitability of the water under consideration, based on the contents of Na<sup>+</sup> and K<sup>+</sup>, for the different usage including drinking water.</p><p>The results depicted in <a href="#f0006">Figure 6</a> indicate that the Mg<sup>2+</sup> contents in the all samples test are higher than that of Ca<sup>2+</sup>. The contents of those two alkaline elements in the drinking water of the area under study are significantly lower than the limits established by the WHO (<span class="ref-lnk lazy-ref"><a data-rid="cit0046" data-refLink="_i29 _i30 _i31 _i32" href="#"><span class="off-screen">Citation</span>2011</a></span>) (50 mg/L for Mg<sup>2+</sup> and 75 mg/L for Ca<sup>2+</sup>) and the Canadian standards (50 mg/L for Mg<sup>2+</sup>and 200 mg/L for Ca<sup>2+</sup>). However, drinking water has acceptable values for both Ca<sup>2+</sup>and Mg<sup>2+</sup>, which can be a source for diet, and is highly required for people with insufficient intake of Mg<sup>2+</sup> and Ca<sup>2+</sup>. <div class="figure figureViewer" id="f0006"><div class="hidden figureViewerArticleInfo"><span class="figViewerTitle">Groundwater quality and health assessments based on heavy metals and trace elements content in Dakhla Oasis, New Valley Governorate, Egypt</span><div class="articleAuthors articleInfoSection"><div class="authorsHeading">All authors</div><div class="authors"><a class="entryAuthor" href="/action/doSearch?Contrib=Saleh%2C+Hosam+M"><span class="hlFld-ContribAuthor"><a href="/author/Saleh%2C+Hosam+M"><span class="NLM_given-names">Hosam M.</span> Saleh</a></span> <a href="https://orcid.org/0000-0002-5889-3548"><img src="/templates/jsp/images/orcid.png" /></a>, </a><a class="entryAuthor" href="/action/doSearch?Contrib=Eskander%2C+Samir+B"><span class="hlFld-ContribAuthor"><a href="/author/Eskander%2C+Samir+B"><span class="NLM_given-names">Samir B.</span> Eskander</a></span>, </a><a class="entryAuthor" href="/action/doSearch?Contrib=Mahmoud%2C+Hazem+H"><span class="hlFld-ContribAuthor"><a href="/author/Mahmoud%2C+Hazem+H"><span class="NLM_given-names">Hazem H.</span> Mahmoud</a></span> &amp; </a><a class="entryAuthor" href="/action/doSearch?Contrib=Abdou%2C+Mona+I"><span class="hlFld-ContribAuthor"><a href="/author/Abdou%2C+Mona+I"><span class="NLM_given-names">Mona I.</span> Abdou</a></span></a></div></div><div class="articleLowerInfo articleInfoSection"><div class="articleLowerInfoSection articleInfoDOI"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1080/23570008.2021.2018540">https://doi.org/10.1080/23570008.2021.2018540</a></div><div class="articleInfoPublicationDate articleLowerInfoSection border"><h6>Published online:</h6>07 January 2022</div></div></div><div class="figureThumbnailContainer"><div class="figureInfo"><td align="left" valign="top" width="100%"><div class="short-legend"><p class="captionText"><span class="captionLabel">Figure 6. </span> The average concentrations of Ca<sup>2+</sup> and Mg<sup>2+</sup> in the ground waters collected from the 11 sampling positions.</p></div></td></div><a href="#" class="thumbnail" aria-label="thumbnail image"><img id="f0006image" src="/na101/home/literatum/publisher/tandf/journals/content/twas20/2022/twas20.v036.i01/23570008.2021.2018540/20221215/images/medium/twas_a_2018540_f0006_oc.jpg" loading="lazy" height="260" width="500" /></a><div class="figureDownloadOptions"><a href="#" class="downloadBtn btn btn-sm" role="button">Display full size</a></div></div></div><div class="hidden rs_skip" id="fig-description-f0006"><p class="captionText"><span class="captionLabel">Figure 6. </span> The average concentrations of Ca<sup>2+</sup> and Mg<sup>2+</sup> in the ground waters collected from the 11 sampling positions.</p></div><div class="hidden rs_skip" id="figureFootNote-f0006"><div class="figureFootNote-f0006"></div></div></p><p>The health risks of hard water are mainly attributed to the impact of the salts dissolved in it, basically Ca<sup>2+</sup> and Mg<sup>2+</sup> salts. Hence, and according to Sengupta (<span class="ref-lnk lazy-ref"><a data-rid="cit0035" data-refLink="_i29 _i30 _i31 _i32" href="#"><span class="off-screen">Citation</span>2013</a></span>), the water samples collected from the 11 sampling positions can be considered soft water since their average dissolved Ca<sup>2+</sup>and Mg<sup>2+</sup>concentrations were lower than the upper limit for soft water (60 mg/L) (<button class="ref showTableEventRef" data-ID="t0004">Table 4</button>). Therefore, the population in the studied area who are dependent on the groundwater for satisfying their drinking water are not in need for extra intakes of both Ca and Mg elements. Consequently, they do not suffer from the known adverse health impacts of the hard water consumption.</p><p>The characterization of the groundwater in the area under investigation using Rader diagram (<a href="#f0007">Figure 7</a>) shows that, for all the eleven sampling points, the Na<sup>+</sup>+ K<sup>+</sup> percentages are more dominant than Ca<sup>2+</sup>+ Mg<sup>2+</sup> percentages. Therefore, the water samples taken in this area can be categorized as alkali rather than alkaline type. This again confirms that the groundwaters in Dakhla Oasis are nearly first grade soft water and suitable for all the citizens in that area and can be safely used for all their daily activities. <div (<span class="ref-lnk lazy-ref"><a data-rid="cit0023" data-refLink="_i29 _i30 _i31 _i32" href="#"><span class="off-screen">Citation</span>2019</a></span>). : &quot;image&quot;, &quot;src&quot; : &quot;/na101/home/literatum/publisher/tandf/journals/content/twas20/2022/twas20.v036.i01/23570008.2021.2018540/20221215/images/twas_a_2018540_m0003.gif&quot;}" /><span class="mml-formula"><span class="disp_formula_label_div"><span id="m0003" class="disp-formula-label">(3) </span></span></span></span><span class="NLM_disp-formula disp-formula rs_preserve"><img src="//:0" alt="" data-formula-source="{&quot;type&quot; : &quot;mathjax&quot;}" /><math><mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">W</mi><mi mathvariant="normal">Q</mi><mi mathvariant="normal">I</mi><mo>=</mo></mrow></mrow><mo>â</mo><mspace width="thinmathspace"></mspace><mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">S</mi><mi mathvariant="normal">i</mi></mrow></mrow></math><span class="mathjaxLabel"><span class="disp_formula_label_div"><span id="m0003" class="disp-formula-label">(3) </span></span></span></span></disp-formula-group></p><p>Where <disp-formula-group><span class="NLM_disp-formula-image disp-formula rs_preserve"><noscript><img src="/na101/home/literatum/publisher/tandf/journals/content/twas20/2022/twas20.v036.i01/23570008.2021.2018540/20221215/images/twas_a_2018540_um0001.gif" alt="" /></noscript><img src="//:0" alt="" class="mml-formula" data-formula-source="{&quot;type&quot; : &quot;image&quot;, &quot;src&quot; : &quot;/na101/home/literatum/publisher/tandf/journals/content/twas20/2022/twas20.v036.i01/23570008.2021.2018540/20221215/images/twas_a_2018540_um0001.gif&quot;}" /><span class="mml-formula"></span></span><span class="NLM_disp-formula disp-formula rs_preserve"><img src="//:0" alt="" data-formula-source="{&quot;type&quot; : &quot;mathjax&quot;}" /><math><mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">S</mi><mi mathvariant="normal">i</mi><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant="normal">W</mi><mi mathvariant="normal">i</mi><mi mathvariant="normal">x</mi><mi mathvariant="normal">Q</mi><mi mathvariant="normal">i</mi></mrow></mrow></math></span></disp-formula-group></p><p>According to the Water quality Index Classification Ranges reported by RadFard et al. (<span class="ref-lnk lazy-ref"><a data-rid="cit0023" data-refLink="_i29 _i30 _i31 _i32" href="#"><span class="off-screen">Citation</span>2019</a></span>), the water quality classification ranges and types of water are categorized as follows: the value &lt;50 is excellent and good for human health. Between 50 and 100 is good and fit for human consumption. Range 100â200 is poor water and not in good condition while between 200 and 300 is very poor and needs attention before use. Finley &gt;300 is inappropriate and needs attention before use. Therefore, it can be stated that the calculated WQIâs value for the groundwater of Dakhla Oasis is less than 50 (<button class="ref showTableEventRef" data-ID="t0006">Table 6</button>).<div class="tableViewerArticleInfo hidden"><span class="figViewerTitle">Groundwater quality and health assessments based on heavy metals and trace elements content in Dakhla Oasis, New Valley Governorate, Egypt</span><div class="articleAuthors articleInfoSection"><div class="authorsHeading">All authors</div><div class="authors"><a class="entryAuthor" href="/action/doSearch?Contrib=Saleh%2C+Hosam+M"><span class="hlFld-ContribAuthor"><a href="/author/Saleh%2C+Hosam+M"><span class="NLM_given-names">Hosam M.</span> Saleh</a></span> <a href="https://orcid.org/0000-0002-5889-3548"><img src="/templates/jsp/images/orcid.png" /></a>, </a><a class="entryAuthor" href="/action/doSearch?Contrib=Eskander%2C+Samir+B"><span class="hlFld-ContribAuthor"><a href="/author/Eskander%2C+Samir+B"><span class="NLM_given-names">Samir B.</span> Eskander</a></span>, </a><a class="entryAuthor" href="/action/doSearch?Contrib=Mahmoud%2C+Hazem+H"><span class="hlFld-ContribAuthor"><a href="/author/Mahmoud%2C+Hazem+H"><span class="NLM_given-names">Hazem H.</span> Mahmoud</a></span> &amp; </a><a class="entryAuthor" href="/action/doSearch?Contrib=Abdou%2C+Mona+I"><span class="hlFld-ContribAuthor"><a href="/author/Abdou%2C+Mona+I"><span class="NLM_given-names">Mona I.</span> Abdou</a></span></a></div></div><div class="articleLowerInfo articleInfoSection"><div class="articleLowerInfoSection articleInfoDOI"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1080/23570008.2021.2018540">https://doi.org/10.1080/23570008.2021.2018540</a></div><div class="articleInfoPublicationDate articleLowerInfoSection border"><h6>Published online:</h6>07 January 2022</div></div></div><div class="tableView"><div class="tableCaption"><div class="short-legend"><h3><p class="captionText"><span class="captionLabel">Table 6. </span> Calculated data for drinking groundwater quality index (WQI) of Dakhla Oasis based on (RadFard et al., <span class="ref-lnk lazy-ref"><a data-rid="cit0023" data-refLink="_i29 _i30 _i31 _i32" href="#"><span class="off-screen">Citation</span>2019</a></span>)</p></h3></div></div><div class="tableDownloadOption" data-hasCSVLnk="true" id="t0006-table-wrapper"><a class="downloadButton btn btn-sm" role="button" href="/action/downloadTable?id=t0006&amp;doi=10.1080%2F23570008.2021.2018540&amp;downloadType=CSV">
Download CSV</a><a data-id="t0006" class="downloadButton btn btn-sm displaySizeTable" href="#" role="button">Display Table</a></div></div></p><p>Hence, the water samples collected from the eleven locations under consideration are categorized as excellent water classes; consequently, they are recommended as good and safe for human utilization.</p><p>The total dissolved solids (TDS) in drinking water can affect its taste (Dietrich &amp; Gallagher, <span class="ref-lnk lazy-ref"><a data-rid="cit0007" data-refLink="_i29 _i30 _i31 _i32" href="#"><span class="off-screen">Citation</span>2013</a></span>). The mean value of TDS in the water samples collected from the eleven outlets in the area under study amounted to 286 mg/L (<button class="ref showTableEventRef" data-ID="t0007">Table 7</button>). It was reported that the palatability of drinking water has been rated by panels of tasters in relation to its TDS level where the excellent water grade contains less than 300 mg/L (WHO, <span class="ref-lnk lazy-ref"><a data-rid="cit0042" data-refLink="_i29 _i30 _i31 _i32" href="#"><span class="off-screen">Citation</span>2003</a></span>). On the other hand, water with very low level of TDS may also be rejected because of its flat, insipid taste. As a result, the Dakhla Oasisâ groundwater with TDS = 286 mg/L is very close to the limit of WHO rating, definitely to be categorized as an excellent water. This confirms the same conclusion previously stated based on WQI calculations.<div class="tableViewerArticleInfo hidden"><span class="figViewerTitle">Groundwater quality and health assessments based on heavy metals and trace elements content in Dakhla Oasis, New Valley Governorate, Egypt</span><div class="articleAuthors articleInfoSection"><div class="authorsHeading">All authors</div><div class="authors"><a class="entryAuthor" href="/action/doSearch?Contrib=Saleh%2C+Hosam+M"><span class="hlFld-ContribAuthor"><a href="/author/Saleh%2C+Hosam+M"><span class="NLM_given-names">Hosam M.</span> Saleh</a></span> <a href="https://orcid.org/0000-0002-5889-3548"><img src="/templates/jsp/images/orcid.png" /></a>, </a><a class="entryAuthor" href="/action/doSearch?Contrib=Eskander%2C+Samir+B"><span class="hlFld-ContribAuthor"><a href="/author/Eskander%2C+Samir+B"><span class="NLM_given-names">Samir B.</span> Eskander</a></span>, </a><a class="entryAuthor" href="/action/doSearch?Contrib=Mahmoud%2C+Hazem+H"><span class="hlFld-ContribAuthor"><a href="/author/Mahmoud%2C+Hazem+H"><span class="NLM_given-names">Hazem H.</span> Mahmoud</a></span> &amp; </a><a class="entryAuthor" href="/action/doSearch?Contrib=Abdou%2C+Mona+I"><span class="hlFld-ContribAuthor"><a href="/author/Abdou%2C+Mona+I"><span class="NLM_given-names">Mona I.</span> Abdou</a></span></a></div></div><div class="articleLowerInfo articleInfoSection"><div class="articleLowerInfoSection articleInfoDOI"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1080/23570008.2021.2018540">https://doi.org/10.1080/23570008.2021.2018540</a></div><div class="articleInfoPublicationDate articleLowerInfoSection border"><h6>Published online:</h6>07 January 2022</div></div></div><div class="tableView"><div class="tableCaption"><div class="short-legend"><h3><p class="captionText"><span class="captionLabel">Table 7. </span> Chronic Daily Intake (CDI) in mg/kg (BW) per day for the predominated elements through drinking water from the 11 outlets in Dakhla Oasis</p></h3></div></div><div class="tableDownloadOption" data-hasCSVLnk="true" id="t0007-table-wrapper"><a class="downloadButton btn btn-sm" role="button" href="/action/downloadTable?id=t0007&amp;doi=10.1080%2F23570008.2021.2018540&amp;downloadType=CSV">
Download CSV</a><a data-id="t0007" class="downloadButton btn btn-sm displaySizeTable" href="#" role="button">Display Table</a></div></div></p></div><div id="s0003-s2004" class="NLM_sec NLM_sec_level_2"><h3 class="section-heading-3" id="_i20">Human health risk assessment</h3><div id="s0003-s2004-s3001" class="NLM_sec NLM_sec_level_3"><h4 class="section-heading-4" id="_i21">Chronic Daily Intake (CDI) and Health Risk indices (HR) for some selected elements</h4><p>According to the United States Environmental Protection Agency (USEPA) ingestion, inhalation and dermal contact are the main pathways for toxic and heavy metals to enter into the human body (USEPA, <span class="ref-lnk lazy-ref"><a data-rid="cit0040" data-refLink="_i29 _i30 _i31 _i32" href="#"><span class="off-screen">Citation</span>2012</a></span>). The presence of those metals inside the body can be a source of health risks. CDIs were computed for Sr, Na, K, Ca, Mg, Fe, and Ba. To quantify the HR accompanied by Fe, Mn, and Ba in drinking water sources of the area under investigation within Al Dakhla Oasis, a group of parameters were evaluated.</p><p>Chronic Daily Intakes (CDI) through the samples of the groundwater was calculated applying <a href="#m0004">equation (4)</a> adapted from Masok, Masiteng, Mavunda, and Maleka (<span class="ref-lnk lazy-ref"><a data-rid="cit0015" data-refLink="_i29 _i30 _i31 _i32" href="#"><span class="off-screen">Citation</span>2017</a></span>). <disp-formula-group><span class="NLM_disp-formula-image disp-formula rs_preserve"><noscript><img src="/na101/home/literatum/publisher/tandf/journals/content/twas20/2022/twas20.v036.i01/23570008.2021.2018540/20221215/images/twas_a_2018540_m0004.gif" alt="" /></noscript><img src="//:0" alt="" class="mml-formula" data-formula-source="{&quot;type&quot; : &quot;image&quot;, &quot;src&quot; : &quot;/na101/home/literatum/publisher/tandf/journals/content/twas20/2022/twas20.v036.i01/23570008.2021.2018540/20221215/images/twas_a_2018540_m0004.gif&quot;}" /><span class="mml-formula"><span class="disp_formula_label_div"><span id="m0004" class="disp-formula-label">(4) </span></span></span></span><span class="NLM_disp-formula disp-formula rs_preserve"><img src="//:0" alt="" data-formula-source="{&quot;type&quot; : &quot;mathjax&quot;}" /><math><mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">C</mi><mi mathvariant="normal">D</mi><mi mathvariant="normal">I</mi></mrow></mrow><mo>=</mo><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mrow><mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">C</mi><mi mathvariant="normal">m</mi></mrow></mrow><mo>Ã</mo><mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">I</mi><mi mathvariant="normal">r</mi></mrow></mrow></mrow></mfenced><mrow><mo>/</mo></mrow><mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">B</mi><mi mathvariant="normal">w</mi></mrow></mrow></math><span class="mathjaxLabel"><span class="disp_formula_label_div"><span id="m0004" class="disp-formula-label">(4) </span></span></span></span></disp-formula-group></p><p>Where</p><p><span class="NLM_disp-formula-image inline-formula rs_preserve"><noscript><img src="/na101/home/literatum/publisher/tandf/journals/content/twas20/2022/twas20.v036.i01/23570008.2021.2018540/20221215/images/twas_a_2018540_ilm0006.gif" alt="" /></noscript><img src="//:0" alt="" class="mml-formula" data-formula-source="{&quot;type&quot; : &quot;image&quot;, &quot;src&quot; : &quot;/na101/home/literatum/publisher/tandf/journals/content/twas20/2022/twas20.v036.i01/23570008.2021.2018540/20221215/images/twas_a_2018540_ilm0006.gif&quot;}" /><span class="mml-formula"></span></span><span class="NLM_disp-formula inline-formula rs_preserve"><img src="//:0" alt="" data-formula-source="{&quot;type&quot; : &quot;mathjax&quot;}" /><math><mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">C</mi><mi mathvariant="normal">D</mi><mi mathvariant="normal">I</mi><mo>=</mo></mrow></mrow></math></span> Chronic Daily Intake in mg/(kgÂ· day).</p><p><span class="NLM_disp-formula-image inline-formula rs_preserve"><noscript><img src="/na101/home/literatum/publisher/tandf/journals/content/twas20/2022/twas20.v036.i01/23570008.2021.2018540/20221215/images/twas_a_2018540_ilm0007.gif" alt="" /></noscript><img src="//:0" alt="" class="mml-formula" data-formula-source="{&quot;type&quot; : &quot;image&quot;, &quot;src&quot; : &quot;/na101/home/literatum/publisher/tandf/journals/content/twas20/2022/twas20.v036.i01/23570008.2021.2018540/20221215/images/twas_a_2018540_ilm0007.gif&quot;}" /><span class="mml-formula"></span></span><span class="NLM_disp-formula inline-formula rs_preserve"><img src="//:0" alt="" data-formula-source="{&quot;type&quot; : &quot;mathjax&quot;}" /><math><mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">C</mi><mi mathvariant="normal">m</mi><mo>=</mo></mrow></mrow></math></span> The concentrations of elements in groundwater in mg/L.</p><p><span class="NLM_disp-formula-image inline-formula rs_preserve"><noscript><img src="/na101/home/literatum/publisher/tandf/journals/content/twas20/2022/twas20.v036.i01/23570008.2021.2018540/20221215/images/twas_a_2018540_ilm0008.gif" alt="" /></noscript><img src="//:0" alt="" class="mml-formula" data-formula-source="{&quot;type&quot; : &quot;image&quot;, &quot;src&quot; : &quot;/na101/home/literatum/publisher/tandf/journals/content/twas20/2022/twas20.v036.i01/23570008.2021.2018540/20221215/images/twas_a_2018540_ilm0008.gif&quot;}" /><span class="mml-formula"></span></span><span class="NLM_disp-formula inline-formula rs_preserve"><img src="//:0" alt="" data-formula-source="{&quot;type&quot; : &quot;mathjax&quot;}" /><math><mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">I</mi><mi mathvariant="normal">r</mi><mo>=</mo></mrow></mrow></math></span> Daily water ingestion rate in l, average value is 2.2 l.</p><p><span class="NLM_disp-formula-image inline-formula rs_preserve"><noscript><img src="/na101/home/literatum/publisher/tandf/journals/content/twas20/2022/twas20.v036.i01/23570008.2021.2018540/20221215/images/twas_a_2018540_ilm0009.gif" alt="" /></noscript><img src="//:0" alt="" class="mml-formula" data-formula-source="{&quot;type&quot; : &quot;image&quot;, &quot;src&quot; : &quot;/na101/home/literatum/publisher/tandf/journals/content/twas20/2022/twas20.v036.i01/23570008.2021.2018540/20221215/images/twas_a_2018540_ilm0009.gif&quot;}" /><span class="mml-formula"></span></span><span class="NLM_disp-formula inline-formula rs_preserve"><img src="//:0" alt="" data-formula-source="{&quot;type&quot; : &quot;mathjax&quot;}" /><math><mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">B</mi><mi mathvariant="normal">w</mi><mo>=</mo></mrow></mrow></math></span> The mean body weight for the area residence is assumed to be 70 kg.</p><p>The chronic daily intake (CDI) values for the selected elements, namely, Sr, Na, K, Ca, Mn and Ba are depicted in (<button class="ref showTableEventRef" data-ID="t0007">Table 7</button>).</p><p>The CDIs of Sr in terms of groundwater consumption for adults are in the range of 0.002â0.0037 with mean value 0.00297 (mg/kg/day), <button class="ref showTableEventRef" data-ID="t0008">Table 8</button>. The lowest Na CDI value for adults was computed at 0.1758 from the sampling point No (7), while the highest Na CDI 0.64679 (mg/kg/day) for adults was found for the sampling outlet No (6). The mean value for Na CDI was 0.28682 (mg/kg/day). Similarly, the computed mean CDI for K was 0.37477 (mg/kg/day) for adult citizens in the area under investigation. The mean Ca CDIs in terms of groundwater consumption for adults in the eleven locations ranged from 0.09685 to 0.13997 (mg/kg/day). The highest Mg of 0.1415257 (mg/kg/day) for adults was analyzed for the sampling outlet No (4) with mean Mg CDI value of 0.16245 (mg/kg/day). The mean CDIs for Fe, Mn and Ba in terms of groundwater consumption for adults were very low and amounted to 0.00428, 0.00166, and 0.00419 (mg/kg/day), respectively. However, it should be noted that water from sampling points number (6) and (8) were Mn-free. (<span class="ref-lnk lazy-ref"><a data-rid="cit0015" data-refLink="_i29 _i30 _i31 _i32" href="#"><span class="off-screen">Citation</span>2017</a></span>), Adesiyan, Bisi-Johnson, Aladesanmi, Okoh, and Ogunfowokan (<span class="ref-lnk lazy-ref"><a data-rid="cit0002" data-refLink="_i29 _i30 _i31 _i32" href="#"><span class="off-screen">Citation</span>2018</a></span>) and RadFard et al. (<span class="ref-lnk lazy-ref"><a data-rid="cit0023" data-refLink="_i29 _i30 _i31 _i32" href="#"><span class="off-screen">Citation</span>2019</a></span>) it can be concluded that the groundwater samples from the studied area are very safe for consumption by the population in Dakhla Oasis. Moreover, the CDI data approved the results previously obtained for WQI and TDS and confirmed the safety and suitability of water at the studied location for human consumption.</p><p>The annual exposure to the element due to ingestion (EPX <i><sub>ing</sub></i>) or dermal (<i>EPX <sub>der</sub>)</i> were calculated using <a href="#m0005">equations (5)</a> and (<a href="#m0006">6</a>), respectively (USEPA, <span class="ref-lnk lazy-ref"><a data-rid="cit0039" data-refLink="_i29 _i30 _i31 _i32" href="#"><span class="off-screen">Citation</span>2007</a></span>). </a><a class="entryAuthor" href="/action/doSearch?Contrib=Abdou%2C+Mona+I"><span class="hlFld-ContribAuthor"><a href="/author/Abdou%2C+Mona+I"><span class="NLM_given-names">Mona I.</span> Abdou</a></span></a></div></div><div class="articleLowerInfo articleInfoSection"><div class="articleLowerInfoSection articleInfoDOI"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1080/23570008.2021.2018540">https://doi.org/10.1080/23570008.2021.2018540</a></div><div class="articleInfoPublicationDate articleLowerInfoSection border"><h6>Published online:</h6>07 January 2022</div></div></div><div class="tableView"><div class="tableCaption"><div class="short-legend"><h3><p class="captionText"><span class="captionLabel">Table 10. </span> Hazard indices assessment of elements through ingestion and dermal pathways</p></h3></div></div><div class="tableDownloadOption" data-hasCSVLnk="false" id="t0010-table-wrapper"><a data-id="t0010" class="downloadButton btn btn-sm displaySizeTable" href="#" role="button">Display Table</a></div></div></p><p>The noted low hazard indices for all water sources collected from the area under investigation can be attributed to the non-detected concentrations of most hazardous elements, also to the low contents of the detected elements in water samples. <button class="ref showTableEventRef" data-ID="t0004">Table 4</button>. This can be referred to the ability of groundwater in this area to purify itself by the residence time in its aquifer as a consequence of natural interaction processes as dilutions, ion exchanges, precipitation, and sedimentations, which was previously stated (IAEA, <span class="ref-lnk lazy-ref"><a data-rid="cit0013" data-refLink="_i29 _i30 _i31 _i32" href="#"><span class="off-screen">Citation</span>2013</a></span>; Saha, Singh, Srivastavai, Dwivedi, &amp; Mukherjee, <span class="ref-lnk lazy-ref"><a data-rid="cit0024" data-refLink="_i29 _i30 _i31 _i32" href="#"><span class="off-screen">Citation</span>2014</a></span>).</p><p>A comparison between the percentage of numbers of the normal and abnormal levels of urea, creatinine, and CEA for males and females are represented in the following diagrams in <a href="#f0008">Figure 8</a>. The biological results show a low percentage of abnormal kidney biomarkers in males and 100% normal females, since the normal urea level is 5â20 mg/dL, and the normal creatinine level is 0.5â1.5 mg/dL (Tietz, <span class="ref-lnk lazy-ref"><a data-rid="cit0038" data-refLink="_i29 _i30 _i31 _i32" href="#"><span class="off-screen">Citation</span>1990</a></span>). Males and females CEA were by 100% in the normal range, since all results were less than 5 mg/mL (Westgard et al., <span class="ref-lnk lazy-ref"><a data-rid="cit0041" data-refLink="_i29 _i30 _i31 _i32" href="#"><span class="off-screen">Citation</span>1981</a></span>). These results confirm the previous conclusion that the groundwater in the areas under study has no health threats to the citizens there. <div class="figure figureViewer" id="f0008"><div class="hidden for males and females in random population samples from Mut point.</p></div><div class="hidden rs_skip" id="figureFootNote-f0008"><div class="figureFootNote-f0008"></div></div></p></div></div></div><div id="s0004" class="NLM_sec NLM_sec_level_1"><h2 id="_i28" class="section-heading-2">Conclusion</h2><p>Based on the experimental analysis carried out for chosen 21 elements in groundwater samples collected from eleven locations within the Dakhla Oasis, it can be concluded that six elements, viz. the heavy metals Ag, Cd, Cu, Cr, Co, and Ni not detected at all. Eight elements, namely: Sr, Na, K, Ca, Mg, Fe, Mn and Ba were found in nearly all the investigated water samples. The remaining seven elements Al, Pb, Se, Cs, As, Zn and V were detected in some, but not in all samples. Anyhow, for the last fifteen elements, their concentrations were monitored in all the water samples, noteworthy, they were lower than the permitted values recommended by WHO and other associations, even lower than concentrations recommended for drinking water. The obtained results further depicted that anthropogenic activities in or near the Dakhla Oasis exert non-significant health risks to the local population in terms of elements assumed to cause health threats when taken up through water consumption. Moreover, groundwater supplies in the studied area can be a precious source of Mg and Ca for Dakhla OasisÂ´ population in their diet, especially for those who are insufficiently supplied with these two elements. Through the Water Quality Index (WQI), Chronic Daily Intake (CDI), and Health Risk Index (HR) parameters calculated, the present study can be helpful for both residents, in taking protective measures before water consumption, and for the local authorities, to evaluate the various fundamental contributions for safety in rural drinking groundwater supplies.</p><p>The authors, according to the outcomes of their experimental work, recommend that regular monitoring is essential in order to secure excellent drinking water quality, according to the WHO, to consumers in the studied areas. There are insufficient data suggested for minimum and maximum uptake levels for various elements; moreover, there are no official guideline values to be followed. Therefore, further studies are needed to ensure up-to-date data for both residents and officials. However, it is also recommended that considerable efforts must be made to sustain and further improve environmental analyses techniques, in addition, safety regulations need to be introduced by governorate, official services, and industrial managements aiming at keeping all elements concentrations in groundwater bodies within its aquifers specification at the levels permitted. In addition, consumers should be informed about the elemental composition of their water when it has been altered by piped suppliers or treatment plants.</p></div></div><!--/fulltext content--><script type="text/javascript">
